- **Response:**  
  - Retighten hardware after test session.  
  - Use friction‑adding elements (e.g., leather, silicone, or similar) where appropriate to help keep comb from shifting.  
  - Instruct shooter to re‑check tightness periodically.', null, '3.6.4 Loose Hardware After Shooting', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part II.L > 3. Main Content > 3.6 Failure Modes & Diagnosis > 3.6.4 Loose Hardware After Shooting', '["3-6-4-loose-hardware-after-shooting","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-ii-l-3-main-content-3-6-failure-modes-diagnosis-3-6-4-loose-hardware-after-shooting"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:57:33.590816+00', null), ('3a7f36f9-2e06-4bc6-b254-8f05ef923b70', '053bd335-5ad7-49ba-a915-991f3ed97590', '32', '39', 'Aesthetics are tightly bound to **legacy**:

- Many Perazzi owners view their guns as **heirlooms**:
  - Engraving may include:
    - Initials.
    - Family crests.
    - Important dates.
  - Wood finish develops **patina** over time.
- As years pass:
  - The gun becomes part of the owner’s story and family history.

Factory mindset:

- Craftspeople are aware when they work on special guns (e.g., named SC3 builds).
- This awareness:
  - Instills pride.
  - Reinforces the sense that they are contributing to someone’s **personal legacy**.

Emotional experience:

- When the owner opens the case:
  - The combination of fine checkering, engraving, and finish is meant to **spark pride and confidence**.
- Confidence is not trivial:
  - Feeling that the gun is an extension of oneself can improve competitive performance.
- The factory showroom:
  - Uses bright, well-considered lighting and presentation to allow customers to see and appreciate **every aesthetic detail**.', null, '3.4.5 Customization, Legacy, and Emotional Experience', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part III: Cross-Cutting Systems > 3. Main Content > 3.4 Aesthetics & Identity > 3.4.5 Customization, Legacy, and Emotional Experience', '["3-4-5-customization-legacy-and-emotional-experience","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-iii-cross-cutting-systems-3-main-content-3-4-aesthetics-identity-3-4-5-customization-legacy-and-emotional-experience"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:58:22.014078+00', null), ('3a8e6122-77b8-4488-b12d-068ddd38c419', '67ca387d-48bc-4047-9404-209a02645c52', '24', '39', '- At the elite tier, **testing each gun’s on-target performance** is expected:
  - Perazzi pattern-tests individually.
  - Krieghoff uses pattern tunnels for regulation.
  - English houses historically test-fired and regulated each double.
- Distinction from mass-market:
  - Lower-end manufacturers may only spot-check or use sampling.
  - Individual pattern certification is more common in the high-end segment.', null, '3.2.8 Accuracy of Regulation and Pattern Testing', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part IV: Perazzi vs General Gunmaking > 3. Main Content > 3.2 Shared High-End Gunmaking Practices > 3.2.8 Accuracy of Regulation and Pattern Testing', '["3-2-8-accuracy-of-regulation-and-pattern-testing","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-iv-perazzi-vs-general-gunmaking-3-main-content-3-2-shared-high-end-gunmaking-practices-3-2-8-accuracy-of-regulation-and-pattern-testing"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:58:41.686758+00', null), ('3c33e174-f66d-481c-b091-9e11b67ad49a', '67ca387d-48bc-4047-9404-209a02645c52', '34', '39', '- Certain aspects of Perazzi’s performance must be attributed to:
  - **Demonstrable outcomes** (longevity, patterns, feel).
  - Rather than to fully disclosed methods.
- AI systems using this document should:
  - Represent what is known clearly.
  - Clearly state when specifics are **not public**.
  - Avoid speculative technical details masked as fact.

---', null, '3.3.8 Summary: Honest Boundaries', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part IV: Perazzi vs General Gunmaking > 3. Main Content > 3.3 Unknowns & Respect for Proprietary Knowledge > 3.3.8 Summary: Honest Boundaries', '["3-3-8-summary-honest-boundaries","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-iv-perazzi-vs-general-gunmaking-3-main-content-3-3-unknowns-respect-for-proprietary-knowledge-3-3-8-summary-honest-boundaries"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:58:41.686758+00', null), ('3c65de6e-9a4a-491e-a94f-638fa776c994', '8078a4a0-2d04-41fd-bd01-ecfc4c710fbb', '4', '50', '### Kim Rhode
**Country:** United States
**Event:** Women’s Double Trap
**Medal:** Gold
**Olympics:** 1996 Atlanta
**Perazzi platform:** MX12
**Highlights:** At just 17, Rhode won double trap gold in Atlanta 1996 using a Perazzi MX12:contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}. She praised the gun’s reliability over millions of shots, saying she “never had a reliability problem with Perazzi” in her career:contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}. Rhode’s victory was the first of many Olympic medals she earned with Perazzi shotguns.
**Sources:**
- Wikipedia – Olympic use (Perazzi):contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}
- Roger Rule Q&A (Kim Rhode quote on Perazzi reliability):contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}', null, '### Kim Rhode', 'Olympic Medals > Kim Rhode', '["olympic-medals","kim-rhode"]', '["Prospect","Owner"]', '["Loyalist","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:52:20.792823+00', null), ('3ca77b3a-4364-42b1-9cc9-5ee72aa347fd', '70499c1f-6a48-44b7-804a-fc63b2ea9317', '21', '35', 'Mistakes at this station are costly because the receiver is the serialized core of the gun. Representative failure modes include:

1. **Dimensional Errors**  
   - Examples: over-sized locking recess, mis-sized cavities, or incorrect bore diameters.  
   - Consequences: loose lock-up, poor trigger-group fit, or unusable receiver (scrap).  
   - Diagnosis: micrometric checks, go/no-go gauges, CMM measurements.

2. **Misaligned Features**  
   - Examples: firing pin holes slightly off relative to barrel strike points; hinge pin bores out of alignment.  
   - Consequences: misfires, uneven primer strikes, difficult barrel opening/closing.  
   - Diagnosis: specialized alignment fixtures simulating barrel geometry, test fitting with standard barrels.

3. **Surface Defects and Cracks**  
   - Examples: small cracks at corners due to machining stress or material flaws; rough surfaces acting as stress risers.  
   - Consequences: potential structural failure in use.  
   - Diagnosis: visual and magnified inspection; possible dye penetrant testing; experienced machinists feeling surfaces with fingers or stones.

4. **Heat Treatment Issues**  
   - Examples: case hardening that leaves the receiver too brittle or too soft.  
   - Consequences: premature wear (too soft) or risk of cracking (too hard).  
   - Diagnosis: hardness testing; experienced gunsmiths judging how a file bites the surface.

5. **Residual Tool Marks in Critical Areas**  
   - Examples: ridges in seating surfaces or locking interfaces.  
   - Consequences: poor contact, stress concentration, or difficult fitting downstream.  
   - Diagnosis: visual/tactile inspection; corrected via careful hand stoning or re-machining.

6. **Poor Fit With Trigger Group**  
   - Examples: removable trigger group not seating fully or rocking.  
   - Consequences: unreliable ignition, unsafe trigger behavior.  
   - Diagnosis: test-fitting with inspection trigger groups; dimension checks of ledges and locating surfaces.

**Mitigation Strategies**

- Regular calibration of machines, tools, and gauges.  
- In-process inspection after key operations.  
- Test fitting receivers with master barrels, bolts, or trigger groups.  
- Immediate feedback loops from downstream stations (e.g., barrel fitters flagging unusually tight or loose areas) so machining programs and allowances can be adjusted.

Some "failures" are intentionally absorbed as **hand-fitting work**, provided that enough material remains and safety is uncompromised.

---', null, '3.6 Failure Modes & Diagnosis', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part II.B > 3. Main Content > 3.6 Failure Modes & Diagnosis', '["3-6-failure-modes-diagnosis","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-ii-b-3-main-content-3-6-failure-modes-diagnosis"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:54:34.806094+00', null), ('3cc1bf18-4a75-4f16-b0bf-afac4b3e748f', '1e2052a5-ee5e-4421-83c1-cf4e7172cbf2', '29', '45', '- Strong overhead and raking lights to highlight surface irregularities.  
- Micro-fine abrasives (e.g., rottenstone, automotive polishing compound) for final leveling and gloss.  
- Soft cloths or felt pads for hand buffing.', null, '3.5.3 Inspection & Rub-Out Tools', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part II.I > 3. Main Content > 3.5 Tools & Measurements (Conceptual Level) > 3.5.3 Inspection & Rub-Out Tools', '["3-5-3-inspection-rub-out-tools","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-ii-i-3-main-content-3-5-tools-measurements-conceptual-level-3-5-3-inspection-rub-out-tools"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:56:22.593132+00', null), ('3d090b65-41e1-44c7-9109-ef3f4254b546', '00ee41e2-2a64-4498-9321-fde7e5df53f0', '9', '51', '- **Completed Shotgun**  
  - Fully assembled, test‑fired, fitted, and finished gun from Assembly & Mechanical QC and Final Fitting & Adjustments stations.

- **Order Documentation**  
  - Customer/dealer order sheet with detailed spec (e.g., “MX12, 30\" barrels, 1/2 & 3/4 choke, SC3 engraving #100, grade 4 wood, left-hand stock with 5 mm cast-on, 14.5\" LOP, adjustable comb, factory pad”).

- **Quality & Legal Documents**  
  - Internal inspection checklists from prior stages.  
  - Proof certificate from proof house.  
  - Any ballistic test targets or factory test documentation.

- **Accessories & Packaging**  
  - Factory case (fitted or generic) with appropriate inserts or foam.  
  - Spare parts (e.g., firing pins, springs), tools (stock wrench, choke wrench), choke tubes (if applicable) with container, oil bottle, etc.  
  - Manual, warranty card, and any inspector card or certificate.  
  - Outer shipping carton or packaging materials.

- **Inspection Tools**  
  - Good overhead and directional lighting.  
  - Magnifier or loupe for engraving and fine details.  
  - Flashlight or bore light for interior inspection.  
  - Snap caps for final dry‑fire and ejector checks.  
  - Feeler gauge or fingernail (for checking wood-metal junctions).  
  - Trigger pull gauge (if part of final QA routine).  
  - Scale for weighing the gun (if weight is recorded).  
  - Bore gauge (if bore and choke dimensions are documented at this stage).  
  - Rags and rust-preventive oil/silicone cloth for final wipe‑down.', null, '3.2.1 Inputs', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part II.M > 3. Main Content > 3.2 Inputs & Outputs > 3.2.1 Inputs', '["3-2-1-inputs","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-ii-m-3-main-content-3-2-inputs-outputs-3-2-1-inputs"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:57:55.761534+00', null), ('3d24835d-843b-4263-a37c-b2892433d320', 'dadad96d-904b-4c92-af84-aba4f15f7e85', '0', '48', '- Source: Internal Perazzi USA Document - The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun
