- Have the authority to **hold or return** a gun to any department rather than accept an issue.', null, '3.3.7 Judgment & Authority', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part II.M > 3. Main Content > 3.3 Core Knowledge & Skills > 3.3.7 Judgment & Authority', '["3-3-7-judgment-authority","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-ii-m-3-main-content-3-3-core-knowledge-skills-3-3-7-judgment-authority"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:57:55.761534+00', null), ('4439e322-1f7c-4c87-9111-9b3cc78cba17', '30dc5da6-b9ed-450e-8736-4a6dfce0983a', '22', '40', '- **Rounded Edges**  
  - Pros: more comfortable under heavy, repeated use; reduces risk of chipping.  
  - Cons: overly rounded edges can soften lines and reduce crispness of design.

- **Crisp, Sharp Edges**  
  - Pros: visually sharp, especially around panels or cheekpieces.  
  - Cons: less comfortable and more susceptible to edge damage.

**Practical approach:**

- For Perazzi competition guns, favor generally **rounded, comfortable edges**, preserving crispness only where it contributes to design and not at the expense of durability or comfort.

---', null, '3.4.6 Comfort vs Crisp Edges', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part II.F > 3. Main Content > 3.4 Decisions & Trade-Offs > 3.4.6 Comfort vs Crisp Edges', '["3-4-6-comfort-vs-crisp-edges","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-ii-f-3-main-content-3-4-decisions-trade-offs-3-4-6-comfort-vs-crisp-edges"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:55:32.068221+00', null), ('443b14ab-40ec-4ef0-b3b0-64c010214d27', '30dc5da6-b9ed-450e-8736-4a6dfce0983a', '33', '40', '> **Example vignette (composite, illustrative):**  
> Angelo, a veteran stockmaker, has just finished inletting and shaping a custom Perazzi. He tightens the stock bolt, mounts the gun to his shoulder in one fluid motion, and looks down the rib. Even though the dimensions are not his own, he can sense the harmony of the fit. He hands the gun to a colleague of similar build to the client, or to the client if present. “It comes up naturally,” they remark.  
> Later, a visiting shooter tries the finished gun and says the same thing—no minor adjustments needed. Angelo quietly smiles; he knows that invisible hours of careful inletting, shaping, and checking went into that effortless feeling.

