> Note (from AI): The following is a structured restatement of the original linear process list. All details, roles, and relationships have been preserved, only reformatted for clarity and chunking.', null, '3.3 End-to-End Production Process Map', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part I: Product & System Overview > 3. Main Content > 3.3 End-to-End Production Process Map', '["3-3-end-to-end-production-process-map","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-i-product-system-overview-3-main-content-3-3-end-to-end-production-process-map"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:54:11.853745+00', null), ('ae4e0330-f741-4a2c-bada-bd789b53e20a', '67ca387d-48bc-4047-9404-209a02645c52', '12', '39', '- Actions:
  - Typically **blued** or **nickel-plated** on competition models.
  - Historically used **cyanide hardening**, yielding characteristic gray “tiger stripe” finishes on some older guns.
  - Modern processes emphasize:
    - Surface hardening where needed.
    - Durable, corrosion-resistant finishes (nickel, high-quality bluing).
- Barrels:
  - Frequently **rust blued** (slow rust bluing) instead of hot-salt blued.
  - Reason:
    - Rust bluing is kinder to soft-soldered ribs.
    - Preserves solder integrity and long-term structural security.
- Color case-hardening:
  - Not standard on mainstream competition models.
  - Sometimes offered on special-order or aesthetic builds, using processes designed to avoid warping.
- Endurance orientation:
  - Perazzi’s finishing choices balance:
    - Longevity under heavy use.
    - Maintenance of solder joints and structural integrity.
    - Brand-appropriate aesthetics.', null, '3.1.7 Finish and Endurance Practices', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part IV: Perazzi vs General Gunmaking > 3. Main Content > 3.1 Perazzi-Specific Practices and Innovations > 3.1.7 Finish and Endurance Practices', '["3-1-7-finish-and-endurance-practices","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-iv-perazzi-vs-general-gunmaking-3-main-content-3-1-perazzi-specific-practices-and-innovations-3-1-7-finish-and-endurance-practices"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:58:41.686758+00', null), ('ae90de7f-0603-4474-a364-bb1073b2fca7', '1e2052a5-ee5e-4421-83c1-cf4e7172cbf2', '2', '45', '- **Wood Finishing Station (canonical)**  
  - Synonyms: *Stock Finishing*, *Oil Room*, *Wood Finish Bench*.  
  - Definition: Station where the shaped and checkered stock and fore-end are sealed, colored (if desired), and finished to their final sheen and feel.

- **Wood Finisher (canonical)**  
  - Synonyms: *Stock Finisher*, *Oil Finisher*, *Wood Finishing Technician*.  
  - Definition: Craftsperson responsible for surface prep, color decisions, finish application, pore filling, and final rub-out of wood surfaces.', null, '2.1 Roles and Station', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part II.I > 2. Key Concepts & Glossary > 2.1 Roles and Station', '["2-1-roles-and-station","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-ii-i-2-key-concepts-glossary-2-1-roles-and-station"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:56:22.593132+00', null), ('ae984f38-d292-4bdc-a247-ae542a35c030', 'fae85afb-4054-48f2-a2a6-8d756c851b62', '16', '32', '- **Goal**  
  Fit the fore-end hardware that attaches the fore-end wood to the barrels and houses the **ejector mechanism**.

- **Inputs**  
  - Machined fore-end iron.  
  - Ejector trip rods and springs.  
  - Latch and release parts.

- **Outputs**  
  - Fore-end iron assembly precisely fitted to the barrel set:
    - Latch snaps firmly and securely.  
    - Ejectors trip properly when the gun is fired and opened.

- **Owned by**  
  **Fore-end fitter** (gunsmith focusing on barrel/fore-end interface).

---', null, '3.3.5 Fore-end Iron & Ejector Assembly', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part I: Product & System Overview > 3. Main Content > 3.3 End-to-End Production Process Map > 3.3.5 Fore-end Iron & Ejector Assembly', '["3-3-5-fore-end-iron-ejector-assembly","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-i-product-system-overview-3-main-content-3-3-end-to-end-production-process-map-3-3-5-fore-end-iron-ejector-assembly"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:54:11.853745+00', null), ('af3ecb91-dbfa-471a-92f1-ca028f3c76fc', '053bd335-5ad7-49ba-a915-991f3ed97590', '7', '39', 'At critical junctures, craftsmen perform **in-process checks**:

- **Machining checks**
  - Receivers and monoblocs measured with micrometers and gauges **before** leaving CNC.
  - Example checks:
    - Hinge pin hole spacing.
    - Locking bolt recess depth.
  - Out-of-spec parts are:
    - Re-machined if there is allowance, or
    - Rejected if correction would violate tolerances.

- **“Tight but mating” tolerances**
  - Parts are intentionally machined slightly **oversized**.
  - Final fit is achieved by **hand-filing, stoning, and polishing**, eliminating play.
  - The craftsperson acts as a **“living gauge”**, feeling and correcting micro-variations.

- **Barrel fabrication QC**
  - Visual and mechanical straightness checks by a barrel straightener using:
    - A trained eye.
    - A straightening press.
  - Bore diameters and choke dimensions are gauged with **internal micrometers**.
    - Any variance outside a few thousandths of an inch is re-honed to spec.

Hand-fitting and in-process QC ensure that later stages are not tasked with correcting large accumulated errors.', null, '3.1.2 In-Process QC and Hand-Fitting as Measurement', 'The Making of a Perazzi Over-Under Shotgun – Part III: Cross-Cutting Systems > 3. Main Content > 3.1 Quality Control & Tolerances > 3.1.2 In-Process QC and Hand-Fitting as Measurement', '["3-1-2-in-process-qc-and-hand-fitting-as-measurement","the-making-of-a-perazzi-over-under-shotgun-part-iii-cross-cutting-systems-3-main-content-3-1-quality-control-tolerances-3-1-2-in-process-qc-and-hand-fitting-as-measurement"]', '["Prospect","Owner","Navigation"]', '["Loyalist","Prestige","Analyst","Achiever","Legacy"]', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, '2025-12-11 21:58:22.014078+00', null), ('af64b228-6f09-4d93-aadc-96fd03d2b538', 'dadad96d-904b-4c92-af84-aba4f15f7e85', '32', '48', 'This station actively prevents problems that would be costly or impossible to fix later.

Representative failure modes include:

1. **Stock Blank Flaw Discovered Late**
   - Example: hidden crack or void becomes visible when cutting near wrist or head.  
   - Diagnosis: visual inspection of fresh surfaces and offcuts; tapping to compare sound (sharp ring vs dull thud).  
   - Outcome:  
     - If flaw lies in critical zone (wrist, head) and cannot be carved away, blank must be rejected and replaced.  
     - Stockmaker notes issue in production records and selects a new blank of similar grade.

2. **Mis-Cut or Measurement Error**
   - Example: wrong pattern or CNC program used; comb cut too low; cast cut in the wrong direction.  
   - Diagnosis: measuring finished rough dimensions against spec; mounting on action and visually assessing alignment.  
   - Outcome:  
     - If too much wood has been removed in the wrong place (e.g., comb too low, inletting oversized), the stock is usually scrapped.  
     - Prevented by double-checking patterns and programs before cutting, especially on high-grade blanks.

3. **Tear-Out or Chip-Out**
   - Example: grain splinters near thin edges, butt corners, or head during cutting.  
   - Diagnosis: visual inspection and light sanding to reveal extent of damage.  
   - Outcome:  
     - Minor chips in internal or covered areas may be glued back and become invisible under fit.  
     - Visible, deep chips in exposed areas are often unacceptable; may require starting over with a new blank.

4. **Misaligned Inletting**
   - Example: rough inletting is off-center or skewed, causing uneven wall thickness around action.  
   - Diagnosis: test-fitting receiver or test action, measuring side-to-side thickness.  
   - Outcome:  
     - If within correctable margin, careful hand inletting can bring it to center.  
     - If off too far, the stock may end up too thin on one side, requiring rejection.

5. **Stock Warp After Cutting**
   - Example: blank moves slightly after heavy material removal due to residual internal stresses.  
   - Diagnosis: checking straightness of centerline and fit to action after a rest period (often letting rough stock “rest” overnight or longer).  
   - Outcome:  
     - Minor movement can be compensated by subsequent shaping or controlled bending.  
     - Significant warp may render stock unsuitable.

6. **Fore-end Color or Grain Mismatch**
   - Example: fore-end appears too different from stock after rough shaping.  
   - Diagnosis: visual comparison of rough pieces.  
   - Outcome:  
     - Minor differences can be mitigated later with stain.  
     - Large, aesthetically jarring mismatches may prompt selection of a different fore-end blank.

7. **Dimension Issues Discovered in Test Fitting**
   - Example: rough stock mounted to action reveals drop or cast outside intended adjustment margin.  
   - Diagnosis: measuring actual geometry on action; shoulder checks by skilled staff.  
   - Outcome:  
     - If within margin, later shaping and/or bending can correct it.  
     - If outside margin (e.g., comb too low), stock may be scrapped and restarted.

The station relies heavily on **early detection** and **conservative margins** to avoid losing high-value blanks at later, more labor-intensive stages.

